result.execSummary:
The defendant Caleb D Smalley was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia to Manufacture, Compound, Convert, Produce, or Store Methamphetamine [Modifiers: Repeater], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(3)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Defendant Caleb D Smalley in court, in custody with attorney Brian William Severson.  Clifford Chase Burdon appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Cases called: 16CF288, 16CF216, and 16CF51.  Rights/Elements.  Defendant pled no contest to 16CF51 Ct. 2, 16CF216 Cts. 1 & 2.  Court found guilty.  Judgment was entered.  Court dismissed but read in Ct. 1 of 16CF51 and Cts. 3 &4 of 16CF216.  16CF288 Dismissed but read in.  Court sentenced defendant in 16CF51 Ct. 2 to serve 3 years in prison.  18 months initial confinement and 18 months extended supervision, consecutive to any other sentence currently serving. In 16CF216 Ct. 1 Court sentenced defendant to 3 years in prison, 18 months initial confinement and 18 months extended supervision, concurrent to 16CF51  Ct. 2 of 16CF216 Court sentenced defendant to serve 3 years in prison, 18 months initial confinement, 18 months extended supervision, concurrent to each other and to 16CF51. All of these sentences are Consecutive to any other sentence the defendant may currently be serving, including Columbia County case #11CF11.  Conditions of extended supervision include: AODA and comply.  Submit DNA sample.  Any other counseling per agents recommendation.  16CF51 Ct. 2 $518.00 costs.  16CF216 Ct. 1 $518.00 costs.  Ct.2 $268.00 costs.  All cases have 165 days credit each.  Attorney Severson requested defendant be eligible on these offenses for the Challenge Incarceration program and Substance Abuse program.  State had no objection.  Court granted request.  3:12/4:12.
Plea/sentencing hearing on July 20, 2016 at 03:00 pm.
